Sic, qui pauperiem veritus, &Q “ In like manner, he who, fr'om a dread of narrow circumstances, parts with his liberty, more > precious th'an any metals, shall shamefully bear a master, and be for ever a slave, because he shall not know how to be contented with a little ;” i. e he who, not content with a little, regards the precious boon of freedom as of inferior moment when compared with the acquisition of riches, shall become the slave of wealth, and live in etex-nal bondage. —Metallis. Used contemptuously for divitiis.—42. Oui non conveniet sua res;'&c.
